1 Introduction

1.1 Content

The purpose of this analytical report (2Ome_profile) is to analyse RNA 2â€™-O-ribose methylation (2â€™Ome) profiles using C-score values computed across 112 annotated rRNA sites. The objectives are:

- to evaluate whether the 2â€™Ome profiles of these 112 sites can distinguish samples according to their biological condition in the comp1 metadata column.
- to identify the most variable 2â€™Ome sites, independently of the conditions, and to evaluate whether this reduced set is sufficient to capture the underlying biological structure.
- to identify potential technical biases that may impact the analysis results and require corrective methods.

1.2 Project summary

This 2â€™Ome profile report is generated from the analysis of the project name, which is loaded into the RiboClass object ribo_adj_annot_comp1. The dataset used for the downstream analyses corresponds to a cohort of 12 biological samples, as part of the full dataset. This project was aligned on GRCh38 (gencode annotation V46).
. Each sample is annotated with associated metadata describing its biological and technical context. These metadata are essential for interpreting the observed 2â€™Ome profile patterns and identifying potential technical biases, such as batch effects, or biological variations.

1.3 Method: RNA 2â€™Ome interpretation and annotation

The 2â€™O-methylation (2â€™Ome) dataset consists of C-score values. The C-score represents the level of 2â€™Ome of a given site in a specific sample, ranging from 0 (unmethylated) to 1 (fully methylated). Intermediate values reflect partial methylation (i.e., heterogeneous methylation states across ribosomes within the same cell or across the cells of the sample). The method used to compute the C-score is detailed in the QC report (section 1.3 â€œMethodâ€). These quantitative profiles form the basis for all subsequent analyses, including dimensionality reduction (PCA), hierarchical clustering, and variability assessments.

The 2â€™Ome dataset encompasses C-score values measured for a cohort of 12 biological samples.

2 Global analysis of all annotated sites

In this first analytical section, alterations in rRNA 2â€™Ome are analysed globally, by comparing the 2â€™Ome profiles of the 112 annotated sites.

2.1 Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

The plot illustrates the distance between each sample based on its rRNA 2â€™Ome profile using a Principal Component Analysis (PCA). The percentages in dimensions 1 (PC1) and 2 (PC2) reflect the proportion of data variance explained by these axes. Color indicates the different biological groups. Moreover, this plot helps identify a putative batch effect that can be corrected using the inter-normalization option (ComBat-seq tool) (Paraqindes et al, 2023).

2.2 Heatmap and Hierarchical Clustering

The following heatmap shows the pairwise distances between samples, based on their rRNA 2â€™Ome profile at the 112 annotated sites. Manhattan distance was used to quantify the dissimilarities, and hierarchical clustering was performed using ward.D2 method.

Color indicates the different biological groups. The C-score is represented by colored square:
- 0 = no rRNA 2â€™Ome present in any of the rRNA molecules at a particular site in a sample;
- 1 = presence of 2â€™Ome in all rRNA molecules at a particular site in a sample;
- ]0:1[ = a mixture of un-methylated and methylated rRNA molecules at a particular site in a sample.

This plot helps to identify biological variations and putative batch effects that can be corrected using the inter-normalization option (Combat-seq tool) (Paraqindes et al, 2023).

Heatmap of 112 positions and 12 samples

3 Analysis of most variable sites

In this second analysis section, the objectives are (1) to identify the most variable rRNA 2â€™Ome sites in a dataset as described in Marcel et al, 2021, and (2) to determine whether the minimal rRNA 2â€™Ome profile, restricted to these most variable sites, captures biological context differentially from the whole rRNA 2â€™Ome profile. This analysis is therefore focused on the most variable annotated sites.

3.1 Identification of the most variable sites

To identify the most variable rRNA 2â€™Ome sites, the variability of the C-score is assessed using their Interquartile Range (IQR) among all the samples.
The boxplot displays the C-score values for all the samples and for each individual site, and is ordered in decreasing IQR.

The scatter plot shows the IQR values of the C-scores at each 2â€™Ome site among all the samples, displayed in order of decreasing variability (left). The IQR distribution is displayed using a curve (right) that identifies the most variable sites (i.e., those whose IQR is > median + 2 x (median absolute deviation)). These sites are shown in red.

The computed threshold value in this case is :
median + 2 x median absolute deviation = 0.0312544.

This threshold allows the identification of the most variable rRNA 2â€™Ome sites, resulting in the selection of a minimal set of 24 sites for use in the subsequent analysis.

3.2 Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

The plot illustrates the distance between each sample based on its rRNA 2â€™Ome profile, restricted to the 24 most variable annotated sites, using a Principal Component Analysis (PCA). The percentages in dimensions 1 (PC1) and 2 (PC2) reflect the proportion of total variance explained by these axes. As in the full-site analysis (see Section 2.1), this reduced PCA -based on the most variable rRNA 2â€™Ome- enables us to assess whether these positions alone are sufficient for distinguishing between biological groups.

Color indicates the different biological groups. Moreover, this plot helps to identify a putative batch effect that can be corrected using the inter-normalization option (ComBat-seq tool) (Paraqindes et al, 2023).

3.3 Heatmap and Hierarchical Clustering

The heatmap shows the pairwise distances between samples, based on their reduced RNA 2â€™Ome profile, based on the 24 most variable annotated sites. Manhattan distance was used to quantify the dissimilarities, and hierarchical clustering was performed using ward.D2 method.

Color indicates the different biological groups. C-score is represented by colored square:
- 0 = no 2â€™Ome present in any of the rRNA molecules at a particular site in a sample;
- 1 = presence of 2â€™Ome in all rRNA molecules at a particular site in a sample;
- ]0:1[ = a mixture of un-methylated and methylated rRNA molecules at a particular site in a sample.

This plot helps to identify putative batch effects that can be corrected using the inter-normalization option (Combat-seq tool) (Paraqindes et al, 2023).

5 Conclusion

5.1 Analytical synthesis

This 2ome_profile report was generated for the project name. 12 biological samples were analyzed across 112 annotated rRNA 2â€™O-methylation (2â€™Ome) sites. The initial analysis included a Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and a heatmap with hierarchical clustering, both of which were performed using all sites. Next, a subset including the 24 most variable sites was identified based on interquartile range (IQR) metrics, and the same analyses (PCA and heatmap) were repeated using only this reduced set.
